  db.items.insert({
    id: 2080,
    title: "Lifestyle modifications",
    pageType: "content",
    content: '<div class="level-1">Lifestyle modifications</div><div class="level-2">All adults with hypertension should be encouraged to implement lifestyle interventions that should be continued throughout management. Lifestyle modifications have been shown to directly reduce blood pressure by the following amounts:</div><table><tr><th>Lifestyle modification</th><th>Approximate systolic BP reduction range</th></tr><tr><td>1. Weight reduction</td><td>5-20 mmHG/10 kg weight loss</td></tr><tr><td>2. DASH eating plan</td><td>8-14 mmHg</td></tr><tr><td>3. Dietary sodium reduction</td><td>2-8 mmHg</td></tr><tr><td>4. Physical activity</td><td>4-9 mmHg</td></tr><tr><td>5. Moderation of alcohol consumption</td><td>2-4 mmHg</td></tr></table><div class="level-2"><br/><div class="emphasis">Weight reduction:</div> Maintain normal body weight (body mass index 18.5-24.9 kg/m2).<div class="emphasis">Adopt DASH eating plan:</div> Consume a diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and low fat dairy products with a reduced content of saturated and total fat.<div class="emphasis">Dietary sodium reduction:</div> Reduce dietary sodium intake to no more than 100 mmol per day (2.4 g sodium or 6 g sodium chloride).<div class="emphasis">Physical activity:</div> Engage in regular aerobic physical activity such as brisk walking (at least 30 min per day, most days of the week).<div class="emphasis">Moderation of alcohol consumption</div> Limit consumption to no more than 2 drinks (e.g., 24 oz beer, 10 oz wine, or 3 oz 80-proof whiskey) per day in most men, and to no more than 1 drink per day in women and lighter weight persons.</div>'
  });

  db.items.insert({
    id: 2081,
    title: "First-line medications",
    pageType: "content",
    content: '<div class="level-1">First-line medications</div><div class="level-2">The table below outlines the first antihypertensive medications of choice for various demographics and comorbid conditions:</div><table><tr><th>Population (age &#8805; 18 years old)</th><th>Recommended Agents</th></tr><tr><td>General non-black population</td><td>ACE inhibitor, ARB, calcium channel blocker, or thiazide diuretic</td></tr><tr><td>General black population</td><td>Calcium channel blocker or thiazide diuretic</td></tr><tr><td>With chronic kidney disease</td><td>ACE inhibitor or ARB</td></tr><tr><td>With diabetes mellitus</td><td>ACE inhibitor, ARB, calcium channel blocker, or thiazide diuretic</td></tr></table><div class="level-2">In choosing a medication to initiate for the treatment of hypertension, JNC 8 simplified the approach for the general non-black population. Physicians can choose any one of four agents for initial therapy: ACE inhibitor, ARB, calcium channel blocker, or thiazide diuretic. For the general black population, including those with diabetes, a thiazide diuretic or calcium channel blocker should be started. For all patients, regardless of race or age, if chronic kidney disease is present, with or without proteinuria, then initiate an ACE inhibitor or ARB. Lastly, JNC 8 has dropped the recommendation about preferentially picking an ACE inhibitor or ARB for patients with diabetes.</div><br/><div class="level-2">Beta-blockers and alpha-blockers are not considered options for the initial management of hypertension. JNC8 does not recommend beta-blockers as first-line drug because of studies showing a higher rate of cardiovascular morbidity and mortality (e.g., strokes, myocardial infarctions). Alpha-blockers are not recommended as first-line drug because studies found worse rates of heart failure, cardiovascular and cerebrovascular outcomes.</div><br/><div class="level-2">Loop diuretics, direct vasodilators (e.g., hydralazine), alpha-1/beta-blocking agents (e.g., carvedilol), central alpha-2 adrenergic agonists (e.g., clonidine) and vasodilating beta-blockers (e.g., nebivolol) are all not recommended as first-line agents because of a lack of good randomized control trials.</div>'
  });

  db.items.insert({
    id: 2082,
    title: "Target BP goals",
    pageType: "content",
    content: '<div class="level-1">Target BP goals</div><table><tr><th>Age</th><th>Population</th><th>BP Goal</th></tr><tr><td>Age < 60 years old</td><td>General Population</td><td>< 140/90</td></tr><tr><td>Age &#8805; 60 years old</td><td>General Population</td><td>< 150/90</td></tr><tr><td>All ages</td><td>With diabetes mellitus or chronic kidney disease</td><td>< 140/90</td></tr></table><div class="level-2">According to JNC8, in the general population <60 years, lower the BP to <140/90 mm Hg.</div><br/><div class="level-2">In the general population aged ≥60 years, the goal BP is <150/90 mm Hg. If treatment of this population achieves a lower systolic blood pressure (e.g., <140 mm Hg) and treatment is well tolerated, treatment does not need to be adjusted.</div><br/><div class="level-2">In the population aged ≥18 years with diabetes or chronic kidney disease, lower the blood pressure to <140/90 mm Hg.</div>'
  });

  db.items.insert({
    id: 2083,
    title: "Initial testing",
    pageType: "nav",
    items: [
      {
        id: 20830,
        title: "EKG",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">EKG</div><div class="level-2">An electrocardiogram is indicated to assess rate and rhythm issues such as bradycardia, tachycardia, or an underlying heart block. Beta-blockers or calcium channel blockers may be contraindicated for people with abnormal rates or rhythms. You can also look for evidence of ischemic disease, previously undiagnosed myocardial infarctions, or cardiac hypertrophy. Left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH) is the second best prognostic factor for death in all people with or without hypertension. LVH is reversible with proper attention and medical management. The first and best prognostic factor for death in all people is age (the older you are, the more likely you are to die).</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20831,
        title: "Urinalysis",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Urinalysis</div><div class="level-2">Urinalysis can check for proteinuria, which can be evidence of hypertensive nephropathy (target organ damage). Urinalysis can also detect glucosuria, which may be evidence of undiagnosed diabetes or poorly controlled diabetes (a potential co-morbid illness and sign of metabolic syndrome).</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20832,
        title: "Blood glucose",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Blood glucose</div><div class="level-2">An elevated random or fasting blood glucose may be evidence of undiagnosed diabetes or poorly controlled diabetes (a potential co-morbid illness and sign of metabolic syndrome). This could possibly affect the choice of the first-line agent used in managing hypertension.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20833,
        title: "CBC",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">CBC</div><div class="level-2">Low hematocrit may reveal anemic states in hypertensive patients. Anemia makes the likelihood of a major cardiovascular event more likely (strokes, heart attacks). If a hypertensive patient is found to be anemic, the underlying cause (i.e. colon cancer or uterine fibroids) must be found and addressed, and the anemia corrected. Anemia may also be the product of target organ damage in moderate to severe end stage renal disease.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20834,
        title: "Serum potassium",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Serum potassium</div><div class="level-2">Several blood pressure medications can cause potassium derangements - angiotensin converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors, angiotensin receptor blockers (ARBs), and potassium sparing diuretics - which all may cause or exacerbate hyperkalemia. A baseline potassium level is necessary for determining any potential changes from antihypertensive therapy. Furthermore, potassium disturbances can occur in Cushing&#39;s syndrome or primary hyperaldosteronism.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20835,
        title: "Serum creatinine",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Serum creatinine</div><div class="level-2">An elevated serum creatinine (or the corresponding low estimated GFR) may be indicative of end organ damage (hypertensive nephropathy) from long-term uncontrolled hypertension. Some blood pressure medications also elevate creatinine such as ACE inhibitors, ARBs, and diuretics.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20836,
        title: "Cholesterol panel",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Cholesterol panel</div><div class="level-2">Obtained after a 9 to 12 hour fast, a lipid profile that includes measurement of high-density lipoprotein (HDL), low-density lipoprotein (LDL), and triglycerides is important. Hypertensive patients require the entire fasting cholesterol panel in order to properly assess lipid co-morbidities as part of metabolic syndrome and the risk of arteriosclerosis. These patients have fasting lipid panels as surveillance of cholesterol problems, not as a general screening tool.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20837,
        title: "Albumin/creatinine ratio",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Albumin/creatinine ratio</div><div class="level-2">The measurement of urinary albumin excretion or albumin/creatinine ratio (ACR) may be useful is generally recommended in all patients (whether or not they have diabetes) > 18 years old because microalbuminuria does appear to have some prognostic implications. Those with chronic kidney disease (CKD) and hypertension should be on ACEI or ARB as they improve kidney outcomes.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20838,
        title: "Serum calcium",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Serum calcium</div><div class="level-2">JNC also recommends serum calcium (Ca) level. One-third of patients with hyperparathyroidism and hypertension may have illness attributable to renal parenchymal damage due to nephrolithiasis. Increased calcium levels can also have a direct vasoconstrictive effect. It is unclear why the increased serum calcium level in hyperparathyroidism raises blood pressure, as epidemiologic studies suggest that a high calcium intake lowers blood pressure. It is also not clear why calcium channel blockers are effective antihypertensive agents.</div>'
      }
    ]
  });

  db.items.insert({
    id: 2084,
    title: "Stepwise approach",
    pageType: "content",
    content: '<div class="level-1">Stepwise approach</div><div class="level-2">1. Implement lifestyle interventions.</div><div class="level-2">2. Set blood pressure goal and initiate blood pressure lowering medication.</div><div class="level-2">3. Select a drug treatment titration strategy:</div><div class="level-3 bullet">Maximize first medication before adding second, or</div><div class="level-3 bullet">Add second medication before reaching maximum dose of first medication, or</div><div class="level-3 bullet">Start with two medication classes separately or as fixed-dose combination.</div><br/><div class="level-2">The recommended second medication may be from the following classes: angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors (ACEI), angiotensin II receptor blockers (ARB), calcium channel blockers (CCB), or thiazide diuretics.</div><br/><div class="level-2">If at subsequent visits, you do not achieve blood pressure control after starting the second agent, then you continue titrating up until the blood pressure is optimal. If at maximum doses of the double combination of medications and the blood pressure is still not at goal, continue adding agents from other classes. Most hypertensive patients will require two or more medications to optimize their blood pressure.<span class="emphasis"> IMPORTANT: Always avoid combined use of ACEI and ARB.</span></div><br/><div class="level-2">Throughout treatment, be sure to continue to encourage and optimize lifestyle modifications.</div>'
  });

  db.items.insert({
    id: 2085,
    title: "Drug considerations",
    pageType: "nav",
    items: [
      {
        id: 20850,
        title: "Thiazide diuretics",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Thiazide diuretics</div><div class="level-2 bullet">May exacerbate urinary incontinence, especially in elderly patients.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Studies have shown that doses above 25mg a day of HCTZ (hydrochlorothiazide) do not decrease BP or morbidity and mortality.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">atch electrolyte levels, especially hyponatremia.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Avoid in patients with gout.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Start at lower doses in elderly who may be very sensitive.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">May slow demineralization in patients with osteoporosis.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20851,
        title: "Beta-blockers",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Beta-blockers</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Check initial EKG and pulse.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">You don&#39;t have to avoid in diabetic patients as the theoretical possibility of masking hypoglycemic episodes has not been shown.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Excellent for use in tachyarrhythmias, atrial fibrillation, migraines, essential tremor, and perioperative hypertension.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Usually avoid in patients with asthma (depending on receptor sensitivity of drug) and in 3rd degree heart block.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20852,
        title: "ACE inhibitors",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">ACE inhibitors</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Watch potassium, sodium, and creatinine levels.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Renal protective.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Reduces microalbuminuria.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">First-line agent in diabetes and renal disease.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Shown to have direct heart remodeling effects.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">A rise of up to 35% above baseline in creatinine is acceptable after initiating use.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">ACE inhibitor cough is common in 15-20% of patients due to bradykinin production.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Angioedema is a serious side effect to monitor in patients.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Avoid in pregnant women (Category C drugs).</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20853,
        title: "ARBs",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">ARBs</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Reduces microalbuminuria and macroalbuminuria.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Shown to have heart remodeling effects.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Avoid in pregnant women (Category C drugs).</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Less bradykinin production, so less cough than ACE inhibitors.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20854,
        title: "Calcium channel blockers",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Calcium channel blockers</div><div class="level-2 bullet">May be useful in Raynaud&#39;s syndrome.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">May be useful in certain arrhythmias.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Often causes leg edema (15-30% depending on different studies).</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Short acting calcium channel blockers are contraindicated for use in essential hypertension and hypertensive urgencies or emergencies.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20855,
        title: "Loop diuretics",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Loop diuretics</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Monitor electrolytes and creatinine.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Start at lower doses in the elderly.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20856,
        title: "Aldosterone antagonists",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Aldosterone antagonists</div><div class="level-2 bullet">May cause hyperkalemia.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Avoid in patients with K ≥ 5 prior to starting meds.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Low dose aldosterone antagonists reduce morbidity and mortality in CHF patients but increase sudden death at higher doses.</div>'
      }, {
        id: 20857,
        title: "Alpha-blockers",
        pageType: "expand",
        expandableContent: '<div class="level-1">Alpha-blockers</div><div class="level-2 bullet">No proven decrease in morbidity and mortality demonstrated in research studies.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Not mentioned in JNC 7 algorithm for treatment of essential hypertension.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Not mentioned in JNC 7 algorithm for treatment of essential hypertension.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Only useful as adjunct in hard to control blood pressure.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">Not mentioned in JNC 7 algorithm for treatment of essential hypertension.</div><div class="level-2 bullet">May be useful in prostatism but should not be used as a first line anti-hypertensive in patients with BPH.</div>'
      }
    ]
  });

  db.items.insert({
    id: 2086,
    title: "Referral",
    pageType: "content",
    content: '<div class="level-1">Referral</div><div class="level-2">Generally, failure to achieve blood pressure goal in patients who are adhering to full doses of an appropriate three-drug regimen that includes a diuretic would warrant referral to a specialist.</div><br/><div class="level-2">Some family medicine physicians feel comfortable treating patients on four anti-hypertensive medications before referring to a specialist if they are not getting results. Some would seek the assistance of a cardiologist or nephrologist if they are seeing target end organ damage such as congestive heart failure or hypertensive nephropathy.</div>'
  });

